#: ../installation.rst:22
msgid "Installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:24
msgid "The latest official **stable** version of OpenShot Video Editor for Linux, Mac, Chrome OS, and Windows can be downloaded from the official download page at https://www.openshot.org/download/. You can find our latest **unstable** versions (i.e. daily builds) at https://www.openshot.org/download#daily (these versions are updated very frequently, and often contain many improvements not yet released in our stable build)."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:32
msgid "Clean Install"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:34
msgid "If you are upgrading from a previous version of OpenShot or are experiencing a crash or error message after launching OpenShot, please see :ref:`preferences_reset_ref` for instructions on clearing the previous ``openshot.settings`` file (for a clean install with **default preferences**)."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:39
msgid "Windows (Installer)"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:41
msgid "Download the Windows installer from the `official download page <https://www.openshot.org/download/>`_ (the download page contains both 64-bit and 32-bit versions), double click it, and follow the directions on screen. Once completed, OpenShot will be installed and available in your Start menu."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:50
msgid "Windows (Portable)"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:52
msgid "If you need to install OpenShot on Windows without Administrator permissions, we also support a portable installation process. Download the Windows installer from the `official download page <https://www.openshot.org/download/>`_, open the command prompt, and type the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:67
#: ../installation.rst:181
msgid "Mac"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:69
msgid "Download the DMG file from the `official download page <https://www.openshot.org/download/>`_, double click it, and then drag the OpenShot application icon into your **Applications** shortcut. This is very similar to how most Mac applications are installed. Now launch OpenShot from `Launchpad` or `Applications` in Finder."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:77
msgid "Linux (AppImage)"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:79
msgid "Most Linux distributions have a version of OpenShot in their software repositories, which can be installed using your package manager / software store. However, these packaged versions are often very outdated (be sure to check the version number: :guilabel:`Help→About OpenShot`). For this reason, we recommend installing an AppImage from the `official download page <https://www.openshot.org/download/>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:85
msgid "Once downloaded, right click on the AppImage, choose Properties, and mark the file as **Executable**. Finally, double click the AppImage to launch OpenShot. If double clicking does not launch OpenShot, you can also right click on the AppImage, and choose `Execute` or `Run`. For a detailed guide on installing our AppImage and creating a launcher for it, see our `AppImage Installation Guide <https://github.com/OpenShot/openshot-qt/wiki/AppImage-Installation>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:94
msgid "Unable to Launch AppImage?"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:95
msgid "Please verify that the ``libfuse2`` library is installed, which is required to mount and read an AppImage. On newer versions of Ubuntu (i.e. 22.04+), ``libfuse2`` is not installed by default. You can install it with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:104
msgid "Install AppImage Launcher"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:105
msgid "If you plan on using OpenShot often, you will probably want an integrated launcher for our AppImage. We recommend using AppImageLauncher, which is the officially supported way to launch (and manage) AppImage files on your Linux desktop. If you are on a Debian-based distro (Ubuntu, Mint, etc...), there is an official AppImageLauncher PPA:"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:117
msgid "Linux (PPA)"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:119
msgid "For Debian-based Linux distributions (Ubuntu, Mint, etc...), we also have a PPA (Personal Package Archive), which adds our official OpenShot software repository to your package manager, making it possible to install our latest version, without relying on our AppImages."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:124
msgid "Stable PPA (Contains only official releases)"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:133
msgid "Daily PPA (Highly experimental and unstable, for testers)"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:142
msgid "Chrome OS (Chromebook)"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:144
msgid "Chrome OS supports Linux apps, but this feature is off by default. You can turn it on in *Settings*. Once Linux is enabled, you can install and run OpenShot Linux AppImages on any *x86-based* Chromebook. The command below will download our AppImage and configure your system to run OpenShot successfully."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:149
msgid "Navigate to *chrome://os-settings/crostini* (Copy/Paste)"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:150
msgid "Under \"Linux (Beta)\" select \"Turn On\". Default values are fine."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:152
msgid "When the Terminal appears (i.e. black window), Copy/Paste the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:152
msgid "``bash <(wget -O - http://openshot.org/files/chromeos/install-stable.sh)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:155
msgid "Previous Versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:157
msgid "To download old versions of OpenShot Video Editor, you can visit https://github.com/OpenShot/openshot-qt/tags. Click on the version number you need, and scroll to the bottom, under the release notes. You will find download links for each operating system. Download the appropriate version for your computer, and follow the installation instructions above."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:162
msgid "NOTE: Projects (\\*.osp) made with newer versions of OpenShot Video Editor might not support older versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:165
msgid "Uninstall"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:167
msgid "To fully uninstall OpenShot from your system, you must **manually delete** the ``.openshot_qt`` folder: ``~/.openshot_qt/`` or ``C:\\Users\\USERNAME\\.openshot_qt\\``, which contains all settings and files used by OpenShot. Be sure to **backup** any recovery files of your existing projects first (\\*.osp files). Please see :ref:`preferences_reset_ref` for instructions on clearing the previous ``openshot.settings`` file (for a clean install with **default preferences**)."
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:174
msgid "Windows"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:176
msgid "Open **Control Panel** from the Start menu"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:177
msgid "Click on **Programs and Features**"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:178
msgid "Select OpenShot Video Editor, then click **Uninstall**"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:183
msgid "Open **Finder** and go to **Applications**"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:184
msgid "Drag the OpenShot Video Editor icon to the **Trash** in the Dock"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:185
msgid "Right-click **Trash** and choose **Empty Trash**"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:188
msgid "Ubuntu (Linux)"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:190
msgid "Open up **Files**"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:191
msgid "Locate the ``*.AppImage`` and delete the file"
msgstr ""

#: ../installation.rst:192
msgid "OR click Activities, Right-click on OpenShot Video Editor icon, and choose **Remove AppImage from System**"
msgstr ""
